{
  "text": "Faf protein antagonizes ubiquitination and proteasome-mediated degradation of its target proteins [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Interestingly, Faf was recently reported to stimulate a Drosophila neuronal JNK signaling pathway that is regulated by the MAPKKK Wallenda (Wnd) [CITATION_3] , a homolog of dual leucine zipper-bearing kinase (DLK) that is known to bind JIP1 [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Overexpression of faf leads to increased levels of Wnd (MAPKKK) protein and thereby causes excessive synaptic sprouting through a pathway *Correspondence: bsaxton@indiana.eduthat requires the Drosophila JNK homolog Basket (Bsk) [CITATION_6] . We found that mutating just one copy of wnd blocked the suppression of Aplip1 overexpression by P{EP}faf EP381 ( Figure 1D and Table S1 ). This suggests that faf overexpression suppresses APLIP1 (JIP1)-Klc interaction by elevating the level of Wnd (MAPKKK). Consistent with this, direct overexpression of wnd in neurons with a wild-type transgene (UAS-wnd) was as effective as P{EP}faf EP381 in suppressing UAS-Aplip1-induced axonal accumulation of synaptic proteins ( Figure 1F and Table S1 ). Equivalent expression of a ''kinase-dead'' mutant transgene (UAS-wnd KD ) did not suppress the defects ( Figure 1G and Table S1 ). Thus, Wnd (MAPKKK) and its downstream phosphorylation targets may actively regulate APLIP1 (JIP1)-Klc binding in neurons.",
